## Q5 — CPU Scheduling (Priority Non-Preemptive)

### What is being asked?
5 processes all arrive at t=0 with different burst times and priorities.
Lower priority number = higher urgency (priority 1 runs before priority 2).
Simulate which order they run. Compute waiting and turnaround time for each.

### What is Priority Scheduling?
Instead of first-come-first-serve, the process with the **highest priority** (lowest number) gets the CPU first. Non-preemptive means once a process starts, it runs till it finishes — no interruption.

### Input:
| Process | Burst Time | Priority |
|---------|-----------|----------|
| P1 | 4 | 2 |
| P2 | 3 | 1 |
| P3 | 5 | 3 |
| P4 | 1 | 1 |
| P5 | 2 | 4 |

All arrive at t=0. Lower number = higher priority.

---

### FILE: `priority.c`

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int n = 5;

    int pid[]      = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
    int burst[]    = {4, 3, 5, 1, 2};
    int priority[] = {2, 1, 3, 1, 4};

    // Step 1: Sort processes by priority (lower number = higher priority)
    // If two have same priority, keep original order (stable sort)
    // Using simple bubble sort
    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n - i - 1; j++) {
            if (priority[j] > priority[j+1]) {
                // Swap priority
                int tmp = priority[j]; priority[j] = priority[j+1]; priority[j+1] = tmp;
                // Swap burst
                tmp = burst[j]; burst[j] = burst[j+1]; burst[j+1] = tmp;
                // Swap pid
                tmp = pid[j]; pid[j] = pid[j+1]; pid[j+1] = tmp;
            }
        }
    }

    int ct[5], tat[5], wt[5];
    int current_time = 0;

    // Step 2: Calculate CT, TAT, WT
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        ct[i]  = current_time + burst[i];
        tat[i] = ct[i];           // All arrived at 0, so TAT = CT - 0 = CT
        wt[i]  = tat[i] - burst[i];
        current_time = ct[i];
    }

    // Step 3: Print results
    printf("Priority Scheduling (Non-Preemptive)\n");
    printf("All processes arrive at t=0\n\n");
    printf("P\tBT\tPR\tCT\tTAT\tWT\n");

    float total_wt = 0, total_tat = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        printf("P%d\t%d\t%d\t%d\t%d\t%d\n",
               pid[i], burst[i], priority[i], ct[i], tat[i], wt[i]);
        total_wt  += wt[i];
        total_tat += tat[i];
    }

    printf("\nAverage Waiting Time    = %.2f\n", total_wt / n);
    printf("Average Turnaround Time = %.2f\n", total_tat / n);

    // Step 4: Gantt Chart
    printf("\nGantt Chart:\n|");
    current_time = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < burst[i]; j++) printf("-");
        printf("P%d|", pid[i]);
        current_time += burst[i];
    }
    printf("\n0");
    current_time = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        current_time += burst[i];
        for (int j = 0; j < burst[i]; j++) printf(" ");
        printf("%d", current_time);
    }
    printf("\n");

    return 0;
}
```

---

### Explanation:

**After sorting by priority:**
- P2 (priority 1) → runs first
- P4 (priority 1) → same priority as P2, keeps original order → runs second
- P1 (priority 2) → runs third
- P3 (priority 3) → runs fourth
- P5 (priority 4) → runs last

**Calculations (all arrive at t=0):**
| Process | Priority | Burst | CT | TAT | WT |
|---------|----------|-------|----|-----|----|
| P2 | 1 | 3 | 3 | 3 | 0 |
| P4 | 1 | 1 | 4 | 4 | 3 |
| P1 | 2 | 4 | 8 | 8 | 4 |
| P3 | 3 | 5 | 13 | 13 | 8 |
| P5 | 4 | 2 | 15 | 15 | 13 |

Average WT = (0+3+4+8+13)/5 = **5.6**
Average TAT = (3+4+8+13+15)/5 = **8.6**

---

### Compile and Run:
```bash
