## Q7 — Shared Memory (Stock price counter with semaphores)

### What is being asked?
Two processes share a stock price counter via shared memory. A **writer** increments it 10 times. A **reader** reads and prints it each time. Use semaphores to prevent race conditions.

### What's new compared to Q7 Set A?
Here we add **semaphores** to synchronize access — so the reader doesn't read while the writer is writing.

System calls:
- `shmget()` → Create shared memory
- `shmat()` → Attach pointer to it
- Semaphores: `semget()`, `semop()` for locking

---

### FILE 1: `stock_writer.c`

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <sys/ipc.h>
#include <sys/shm.h>
#include <sys/sem.h>   // For semaphores
#include <unistd.h>

#define SHM_KEY 5678
#define SEM_KEY 5679

// Semaphore operation helper functions
void sem_lock(int semid) {
    struct sembuf op = {0, -1, 0};  // Decrement (wait/lock)
    semop(semid, &op, 1);
}

void sem_unlock(int semid) {
    struct sembuf op = {0, 1, 0};   // Increment (signal/unlock)
    semop(semid, &op, 1);
}

int main() {
    // Create shared memory for 1 integer (the stock price)
    int shmid = shmget(SHM_KEY, sizeof(int), IPC_CREAT | 0666);
    if (shmid < 0) { printf("Writer: shmget failed\n"); return 1; }

    // Attach to shared memory
    int *price = (int*) shmat(shmid, NULL, 0);
    if (price == (int*)-1) { printf("Writer: shmat failed\n"); return 1; }

    // Create semaphore (starts at 1 = unlocked)
    int semid = semget(SEM_KEY, 1, IPC_CREAT | 0666);
    semctl(semid, 0, SETVAL, 1);   // Initialize semaphore to 1

    *price = 100;  // Starting stock price

    printf("Writer: Starting. Initial price = %d\n", *price);

    // Increment price 10 times
    for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
        sem_lock(semid);       // Lock before writing
        (*price) += 10;        // Increment price by 10
        printf("Writer: Updated price to %d\n", *price);
        sem_unlock(semid);     // Unlock after writing
        sleep(1);              // Wait 1 second between updates
    }

    shmdt(price);
    printf("Writer: Done.\n");
    return 0;
}
```

---

### FILE 2: `stock_reader.c`

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <sys/ipc.h>
#include <sys/shm.h>
#include <sys/sem.h>
#include <unistd.h>

#define SHM_KEY 5678
#define SEM_KEY 5679

void sem_lock(int semid) {
    struct sembuf op = {0, -1, 0};
    semop(semid, &op, 1);
}

void sem_unlock(int semid) {
    struct sembuf op = {0, 1, 0};
    semop(semid, &op, 1);
}

int main() {
    // Get existing shared memory
    int shmid = shmget(SHM_KEY, sizeof(int), 0666);
    if (shmid < 0) { printf("Reader: shmget failed — run writer first!\n"); return 1; }

    int *price = (int*) shmat(shmid, NULL, 0);
    if (price == (int*)-1) { printf("Reader: shmat failed\n"); return 1; }

    int semid = semget(SEM_KEY, 1, 0666);

    printf("Reader: Starting. Reading price 10 times...\n");

    // Read price 10 times
    for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
        sem_lock(semid);       // Lock before reading
        printf("Reader: Current price = %d\n", *price);
        sem_unlock(semid);     // Unlock after reading
        sleep(1);
    }

    // Clean up shared memory and semaphore
    shmdt(price);
    shmctl(shmid, IPC_RMID, NULL);    // Destroy shared memory
    semctl(semid, 0, IPC_RMID);       // Destroy semaphore

    printf("Reader: Done. Shared memory and semaphore destroyed.\n");
    return 0;
}
```

---

### Explanation:

| Function | What it does |
|----------|-------------|
| `semget(SEM_KEY, 1, IPC_CREAT\|0666)` | Creates 1 semaphore with the given key |
| `semctl(semid, 0, SETVAL, 1)` | Sets semaphore value to 1 (unlocked state) |
| `sem_lock()` — `sembuf op = {0, -1, 0}` | Decrements semaphore. If it hits 0, process blocks |
| `sem_unlock()` — `sembuf op = {0, 1, 0}` | Increments semaphore. Wakes up any waiting process |
