## Q8 — IPC Classical Problems (Dining Philosophers)

### What is being asked?
3 philosophers share 3 forks. Each philosopher needs **both left and right fork** to eat. Without care, they can deadlock (each picks up one fork and waits forever for the other).

Implement the problem and add a **deadlock prevention strategy** (one philosopher picks up right fork first instead of left).

### The Problem:
- Philosopher 0: picks left fork 0, then right fork 1
- Philosopher 1: picks left fork 1, then right fork 2
- Philosopher 2: picks left fork 2, then right fork 0 ← **This one reverses order!**

By making one philosopher pick right fork first, the circular wait is broken → no deadlock.

---

### FILE: `dining.c`

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <pthread.h>
#include <unistd.h>

#define N 3   // Number of philosophers and forks

pthread_mutex_t fork_mutex[N];   // Each fork is a mutex

void think(int id) {
    printf("Philosopher %d is THINKING\n", id);
    usleep(500000);  // Think for 0.5 seconds
}

void eat(int id) {
    printf("Philosopher %d is EATING\n", id);
    usleep(500000);  // Eat for 0.5 seconds
}

void* philosopher(void* arg) {
    int id = *((int*)arg);
    int left  = id;             // Left fork index
    int right = (id + 1) % N;  // Right fork index

    for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {   // Each philosopher eats 3 times
        think(id);

        // Deadlock Prevention:
        // Last philosopher (id = N-1) picks RIGHT fork first, then LEFT
        // All others pick LEFT first, then RIGHT
        // This breaks the circular wait condition
        if (id == N - 1) {
            // Philosopher 2: picks right (0) first, then left (2)
            printf("Philosopher %d picks up RIGHT fork %d\n", id, right);
            pthread_mutex_lock(&fork_mutex[right]);

            printf("Philosopher %d picks up LEFT fork %d\n", id, left);
            pthread_mutex_lock(&fork_mutex[left]);
        } else {
            // Philosophers 0 and 1: picks left first, then right
            printf("Philosopher %d picks up LEFT fork %d\n", id, left);
            pthread_mutex_lock(&fork_mutex[left]);

            printf("Philosopher %d picks up RIGHT fork %d\n", id, right);
            pthread_mutex_lock(&fork_mutex[right]);
        }

        // Eat with both forks
        eat(id);

        // Put down both forks
        pthread_mutex_unlock(&fork_mutex[left]);
        pthread_mutex_unlock(&fork_mutex[right]);
        printf("Philosopher %d put down both forks\n\n", id);
    }

    printf("Philosopher %d finished eating 3 times!\n", id);
    return NULL;
}

int main() {
    pthread_t threads[N];
    int ids[N];

    // Initialize all fork mutexes
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++)
        pthread_mutex_init(&fork_mutex[i], NULL);

    printf("Dining Philosophers Problem (3 philosophers, 3 forks)\n");
    printf("Deadlock prevented: Philosopher %d picks RIGHT fork first\n\n", N-1);

    // Create philosopher threads
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
        ids[i] = i;
        pthread_create(&threads[i], NULL, philosopher, &ids[i]);
    }

    // Wait for all to finish
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++)
        pthread_join(threads[i], NULL);

    // Destroy mutexes
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++)
        pthread_mutex_destroy(&fork_mutex[i]);

    printf("\nAll philosophers have eaten at least once. No deadlock!\n");
    return 0;
}
```

---

### Why does this prevent deadlock?

Without fix (everyone picks left first):
```
P0 holds fork 0, waits for fork 1
P1 holds fork 1, waits for fork 2
P2 holds fork 2, waits for fork 0  ← CIRCULAR WAIT → DEADLOCK
```

With fix (P2 picks right first):
```
P0 holds fork 0, waits for fork 1
P1 holds fork 1, waits for fork 2
P2 tries to pick fork 0 first — but P0 holds it → P2 blocks
P1 can now grab fork 2 → P1 EATS → releases forks → chain resolves
```

No circular wait → no deadlock!

